 indicates chronic infection","Hepatitis B surface antigen indicates resolved infection","Hepatitis B e antigen indicates low viral replication","Hepatitis B surface antibody indicates immunity from either vaccination or resolved infection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct interpretation is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis B surface antibody indicates immunity from either vaccination or resolved infection\u003C/strong\u003E. HBsAb can develop following either vaccination or natural infection clearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect interpretations are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B surface antibody indicates immunity from vaccination only\u003C/strong\u003E - HBsAb develops after both vaccination and resolved natural infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B core antibody IgM indicates chronic infection\u003C/strong\u003E - HBcAb IgM is actually a marker of acute infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B surface antigen indicates resolved infection\u003C/strong\u003E - HBsAg indicates current infection, not resolution\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B e antigen indicates low viral replication\u003C/strong\u003E - HBeAg actually indicates high viral replication and infectivity\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these serological markers is essential for accurately diagnosing hepatitis B status and determining appropriate management strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatitis B surface antibody (HBsAb) indicates immunity through either vaccination or resolved infection","Hepatitis B core antibody IgM (HBcAb IgM) is a marker of acute infection","Hepatitis B e antigen (HBeAg) indicates high viral replication, while e antibody (HBeAb) indicates low infectivity"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 